Holography is one of the most well-known methods for creating three-dimensional images of various objects by accurately detecting and recreating wave fields. The ability of analog display holography to record a huge amount of information about a three-dimensional scene into a recording medium, the thickness of which, as a rule, does not exceed tens of micrometers, is truly amazing! This is achieved by creating and registering an interference (or sometimes diffraction) field of two waves, which are traditionally called the reference and the object waves. This information is encoded as carrier bands resulting from interference. These carrier bands have an extremely high frequency and are therefore not visible to the naked eye. But if the hologram is illuminated with a wave that is identical in its parameters to the reference wave, then it is possible to accurately reproduce the wave front scattered by the object, and thereby form an image that has the effects of perspective and parallax. The development and improvement of photodetector technologies made it possible to replace analog photosensitive plates with digital matrix photodetectors, in connection with which the concept of "digital holography" that existed before received a new definition. If earlier this term was understood as “a section of holography based on modeling the holographic process using computer technology”, and this term was synonymous with the term “computer holography”, now it is time to separate them.Now, digital holography is understood as a section of holography based on digital registration and numerical reconstruction of mathematical models of object and reference waves, while the old definition can be attributed to computer holography (mainly due to the well-established term “computer synthesized hologram”). Restoration of information about an object in digital holography is carried out through numerical processing. Digital holography makes it possible to carry out an accurate quantitative analysis of the properties of an object, both optical (refractive or absorption index) and physical (mechanical deformations). This method is widely used in various fields of science and technology - in production, biology and medicine, art and museum business. The range of problems solved with the help of digital holography is extensive. This includes: tracking of particle ensembles, analysis of morphological characteristics of cells, measurement of surface relief and non-destructive testing of industrial parts, vibration measurement, sound recording, etc. This laboratory workshop on the discipline "Digital Holography" is addressed to students of the Faculty of Photonics.

The main goal of this course is to instill practical skills in applying the capabilities of the holographic approach to solving practical problems.

Discipline tasks:
1. To introduce the basic principles and variety of approaches used in digital holography;
2.Provide an opportunity to practice the basic data recording schemes in digital holography, the most common and effective approaches to their processing, as well as learn how to extract useful information and analyze the results;
3. Inform about the current state of the industry, show the limitations of currently available technologies and indicate trends in their future development.
